The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, January 10, 2004 				 Infosys net jumps 28% to Rs 328 cr
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, Jan. 9: Infosys Technologies today reported better-than-expected numbers for the third quarter of this financial year, posting a 28 per cent growth in net profit and upped its guidance for the year.																								Net profit for the quarter ended December 31 was Rs 328.14 crore against Rs 256.31 crore in the corresponding quarter last year. This figure was higher than the street expectations of Rs 320 crore.																								Income from software development services and products was Rs 1,235.26 crore for the quarter, an increase of around 29 per cent over the comparable income in the year-ago period.																								Amid signs of the global economy picking up coupled with expectations of stability in prices, the software services major upped its revenue guidance for 2003-04 between Rs 4,823 crore and Rs 4,835 crore, while net profit was revised to Rs 1,232.64 crore. The full-year earning per share (EPS) is now expected at Rs 186.2. This translates into a growth of about 30 per cent in both revenues and net profit.																								Analysts said the strong numbers from Infosys has come despite a rising rupee and an intensive competition in the industry, proving that offshore business continues to hold potential for domestic software services companies. Yet they are concerned about the lack of an upsurge in pricing.																								We have reorganised Infosys to face new challenges  increased expectations from clients, a fast-changing economy and a new competitive scenario, Infosys CEO, president and managing director Nandan M. Nilekani said.																								He added that the company has concentrated on vertical markets and on providing business solutions leveraging technology using the global delivery model.																								Margins during the quarter were maintained at 33 per cent despite Infosys and its subsidiary Progeon adding 3,666 employees in the reporting period, the largest hiring for a quarter.																								Pricing has been stable and despite the largest hiring for a quarter, margins have been maintained, chief financial officer T. V. Mohandas Pai said.																								The better-than-expected numbers today propelled the Infosys scrip to a near three-year high in the intra-day trading. However, unwinding of positions led to the scrip finishing off at Rs 5,805.80, a marginal gain of Rs 33.15 over its previous close. The scrip opened at Rs 5,950 and shot to an intra-day high of Rs 6,129. HDFC Bank net up																								HDFC Bank has reported a 32 per cent growth in net profit to Rs 130.4 crore in the third quarter on the back of an increased demand for retail credit. The bank posted a total income  of Rs 779.4 crore in the reporting period against Rs 640.8  crore in the year-ago period. Net revenues (net interest  income plus other income) stand at Rs 475.4 crore in the  quarter, an increase of 39.5 per cent over Rs 340.8 crore  in the same period last year.
